Required implementation scope

1) Add explicit placement strategy selection for experimental metadata placement

Add an explicit experimental writer/configuration surface that allows selecting metadata placement strategy for graph-supporting metadata.

Acceptable explicit surfaces include:
- crushr-pack --placement-strategy <fixed_spread|hash_spread|golden_spread>
- a combined experimental flag surface that already exists and is extended cleanly
- an internal experiment writer mode used by crushr-lab-salvage, provided the strategy names remain explicit and documented

This must remain opt-in.
It must NOT silently change default archive behavior.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

2) Implement required placement strategies

2.1 fixed_spread

Place graph-supporting metadata copies in simple deterministic separated regions.

Requirements:
- at least three separated placement regions if enough copies exist
- must not cluster all copies in the tail region
- early / middle / late placement is acceptable
- placement must be deterministic and documented

2.2 hash_spread

Place graph-supporting metadata copies using deterministic pseudo-random positions derived from stable archive inputs.

Requirements:
- deterministic across runs for identical inputs
- derived from stable seed material such as archive identity / deterministic build state
- no ambient randomness
- no dependence on wall clock or process entropy
- placement must be documented clearly

2.3 golden_spread

Place graph-supporting metadata copies using a deterministic low-discrepancy spread strategy.

Requirements:
- use a deterministic sequence that produces even, non-clustered coverage of archive space
- implementation may use golden-ratio stepping or another equivalent low-discrepancy method
- keep the external/user-facing strategy name exactly:
  golden_spread
- placement must be deterministic and documented

Important:
Do NOT use the name low_discrepancy in user-facing strategy surfaces for this packet.
Use golden_spread.

